  "prompt": "How much does an author make per book on a translated version of their novel?",
  "response": "The amount an author makes per book on a translated version of their novel can vary significantly based on several factors including the author's contract terms, the book's sales volume, and the publishing industry standards in the respective countries.\n\nGenerally, authors receive royalties from the sale of their books, and these royalties can range from 5% to 15% of the book's retail price. This percentage can differ depending on whether the book is sold in physical format, as an ebook, or in other formats.\n\nIn the case of translated books, the author might also receive additional upfront payments or advance for the translation rights. These payments are typically negotiated between the author (or their literary agent) and the foreign publisher. The advance for translation rights can vary widely but often range from a few hundred dollars to several thousand, based on the anticipated marketability of the book in the new language.\n\nIt's important for authors to carefully review and negotiate their contracts to ensure they are receiving a fair share of the profits from their translated works. Additionally, working with a literary agent can help authors navigate these negotiations and secure better terms. \n\nTo give a concrete answer, if an author sells 10,000 copies of their translated book at $20 each, with a royalty rate of 10%, the author would earn $20,000 from those sales. However, these amounts are highly variable and depend on numerous factors including the contractual agreement, market conditions, and sales performance.",
